               <history>

                  <origin><ab>This manuscript was copied during the reign of <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS5616IyasuI">ʾIyāsu I</persName>, most probably for and by the clergy of the church of <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC2248DabraB">Dabra Bǝrhān Śǝllāse</placeName> in <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC3577Gondar">Gondar</placeName>.</ab>
                     <origDate notBefore="1682" notAfter="1706" evidence="context"/>
                  </origin>

                  <provenance>
                     This manuscript might have been possessed by the church of Madḫānē Alam in Gondar (fol. 1, marginal note). It has been looted by King Tēwodros (1855-68) and ended up in his fortress in Maqdālā, where the British army looted it in 1868. It was then given to the British Library (see the stamp on the guardleaf: "Presented by the Secretary of State for India. Aug. 1868").
                  </provenance>
                  <acquisition>auctioned by British Army, 20 April 1868 (likely purchased by R. Holmes on behalf of the British Museum); presented by the Secretary of State for India, Sir Stafford Northcote, to the Trustees of the British Museum, August 28, 1868; British Museum (as MS Orient. 819), August 28, 1868 to 14 December 1872; deaccessioned by the Trustees of the British Museum, 14 December 1872; <persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS10378Yohanne">King Yohannes IV (1871-89)</persName> asked Queen Victoria to have this manuscript back to Ethiopia. The transfer was done in 1872 (see fol. 163v:  « This volume was returned to the King of Ethiopia by  order of the Trustees of the British Museum- dated Dec. 14 1872. J. Winter Jones, Principal Librarian »). The manuscript remained in the Ethiopian royal collection as it was stored in Enṭoṭṭo Raguēl, founded by King Menelik, when it was microfilmed by the EMML project in 1974. </acquisition>
               </history>

